fields.name: NGC1535
fields.description: This PN, at a distance of about 6000 light years from us, is best imaged with a colour exposure of 5s.

fields.name: NGC2403
fields.description: At 11.5 million light years distant, this galaxy may be a member of the M81/M82 group. It is slightly larger than the Faulkes f.o.v, but a 20s colour exposure images the central part of the galaxy well. In this area, several bright regions can be seen. These are the sites of recent and ongoing star formation.

fields.name: NGC2683
fields.description: This is a nearly edge-on spiral galaxy at a distance of about 30 million light years. It is slightly bigger than the Faulkes f.o.v. but the majority of the galaxy is imaged well with a 20-30s colour exposure.

fields.name: NGC2655
fields.description: This is a lenticular galaxy (a disk galaxy, similar to the Milky Way, but with no spiral arm structure) about 80 million light years away. Its nucleus has a mass of about a billion suns, and when imaged, has a bright central region with a diffuse surrounding halo. Use a colour exposure of 20-30s on this galaxy.

fields.name: NGC2681
fields.description: This is a lenticular galaxy (a disk galaxy, similar to the Milky Way, but with no spiral arm structure) about 45 million light years away in the constellation of Ursa Major. Its centre is thought to contain a black-hole with a mass of about 8 million suns. Use a colour exposure of about 10s on this galaxy.

fields.name: NGC2146
fields.description: This barred spiral galaxy has been part of an interaction with another galaxy, resulting in its peculiar shape. Use a colour exposure of about 30s on this galaxy.

fields.name: NGC2196
fields.description: This is a rather small, face-on spiral galaxy in the constellation of Lepus. Use a colour exposure of about 30s on this galaxy.

fields.name: NGC2247
fields.description: This is a reflection nebula in the constellation of Monoceros. It appears as a faint, hazy circular glow surrounding an 8th magnitude star. A colour exposure time of 30-60s is recommended for this object.

fields.name: NGC2245
fields.description: This nebula originates from the gas and dust reflecting light from a nearby 11th magnitude star. A colour exposure time of 30-60s is recommended for this object.

fields.name: IC446
fields.description: A colour exposure time of 30-60s is recommended for this reflection nebula.

fields.name: IC443
fields.description: This supernova remnant is about 30,000 years old. A neutron star, the remains of the star which exploded, was recently discovered inside this cloud of glowing gas. Use a colour exposure of 45-60s to image this SNR.

fields.name: NGC2903
fields.description: This barred spiral galaxy is approximately 30 million light years away. It has a rather mottled appearance due to the many star-forming regions in its spiral arms which show up as bright spots along the arms. This galaxy is best imaged in colour with a 60s exposure time.

fields.name: M82
fields.description: This is an irregular galaxy in the constellation of Ursa Major, 13 million light years away. It is one of a group of galaxies, and is thought to have recently been involved in an interaction with its close neighbour, the spiral galaxy, M81. It is this interaction which is thought to have caused the dust lanes which are prominent in this galaxy, and visible as the dark patches throughout the galaxy.

fields.name: NGC3184
fields.description: This is a nearly face-on spiral galaxy, about 30 million light years away. It has several bright regions visible in its spiral arms, which are the sites of star formation. This galaxy is best imaged with a colour exposure of approximately 30s.

fields.name: NGC3344
fields.description: This is a barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Leo, about 20 million light years away. Several star forming regions are visible in the spiral arms as bright spots. A colour exposure of 30s is recommended for this galaxy.

fields.name: NGC3521
fields.description: This is a barred spiral galaxy, located approximately 25 million light years away in the constellation of Leo.  Regions of star formationin the arms can be seen as blue patches.  A 30s colour exposure is recommended for this object.

fields.name: M66
fields.description: This barred spiral galaxy has both bright regions in its spiral arms, where stars are forming, and darker lanes where dust is obscuring the light. Also visible in the image is a bright foreground star.

fields.name: NGC7213
fields.description: Distance: 70 million ly. This spiral galaxy is one of the brightest of the spirals in the constellation of Grus. A colour exposure time of 30s is recommended for this object.

fields.name: NGC7410
fields.description: Distance: 76 million ly. This spiral galaxy is seen slightly edge-on, thus appears quite elongated. Use a colour exposure time of 30s on this galaxy.

fields.name: IC1459
fields.description: Distance: 100 million ly. This is an Elliptical galaxy with a supermassive black hole at its centre. Use a colour exposure of about 20s on this object.

fields.name: IC5264
fields.description: Distance: 84 million ly. This edge-on spiral galaxy is best viewed with a 45-60s colour exposure.

fields.name: NGC7418
fields.description: Distance: 63 million ly. This impressive nearly face-on spiral galaxy is best imaged with a 45s colour exposure.

fields.name: NGC7421
fields.description: Distance: 79.6 million ly. This spiral galaxy has a prominent bar at its centre, and appears to sit slightly offset from the centre of its envelope. Use a colour exposure of 45-60s to image this galaxy.

fields.name: NGC7418A
fields.description: Distance: 91 million ly. This spiral galaxy has a brighter central region, with fainter, diffuse spiral arms. Use a 45-60s colour exposure on this galaxy.

fields.name: IC5148
fields.description: Distance: 3449 ly. This beautiful planetary nebula was discovered by an amateur astronomer in 1894. It has a hole at its centre surrounding it's central star, enveloped by a ring of material. Use a colour exposure of 45-60s.

fields.name: HCG37
fields.description: This compact quintet has two dominant galaxies (a, bottom middle and b, middle right).

fields.name: HCG41
fields.description: This group consists of four galaxies.  It is thought that this group is a chance alignment if physically unrelated galaxies.

fields.name: HCG45
fields.description: This group of galaxies is a loose quartet of spiral and S0 galaxies.  A prominent dust lane can be seen in galaxy (a, middle left).

fields.name: HCG49
fields.description: This is a small very compact quartet. Distortions in all the galaxies are evident this is due to gravitational interactions, this is particularly evident in (b, middle left).

fields.name: HCG50
fields.description: This is a small ring shaped quintet of galaxies.  The velocity dispersion of this group is very high, which suggests that the galaxies are orbiting within the gravitiational field of a large concentraion of dark mattter.

fields.name: HCG55
fields.description: This group is a very compact chain of five galaxies. The fifth galaxy (e, second down form the top) is a small spiral galaxy and a dust lane can be seen in (c, second from bottom).

fields.name: HCG56
fields.description: This group consists of five galaxies, three of which appear to be in contact and interacting (b, top middle, c, middle middle and d, right top).  Two of these galaxies (b and d) are radio sources.

fields.name: HCG60
fields.description: This is a compact configuration of galaxies within a larger cluster.  Galaxies (a, bottom right and c middle left) are relatively strong radio sources. Galaxy (b, top right) shows a prominent dust lane which is unusual for an eliptical galaxy.

fields.name: HCG66
fields.description: This is a distant chain of four galaxies. Galaxy (d, bottom right) is quite compact.

fields.name: HCG78
fields.description: This quartet contains only two galaxies (a, middle right and b, bottom right) both have accordant redsifts.

fields.name: HCG80
fields.description: This is a quartet of galaxies.  Galaxy (c, top left) has an unusual shape, also note the faint spiral arms of galaxy (b, bottom left) and the warped disk of (a, top left).

fields.name: HCG82
fields.description: This is a loose quartet with a very high velocity dispersion.  The irregular galaxy (c, middle bottom) is a radio and infrared source.

fields.name: HCG84
fields.description: This group consists of a distant quartet plus a faint galaxy (f, top middle right) which has about twice the redshift of the others.  The bright elliptical galaxy (a, middle left) is a radio source.

fields.name: HCG85
fields.description: This is a small quartet of galaxies.  The bright ellipticl galaxy (a, top right) is a radio souce.

fields.name: HCG92
fields.description: This is a famous group Stephan's Quintet.  It was the first compact group discovered, it is dense quartet plus a bright. low redsift sipral galaxy (a, bottom left). It is generally beleived that galaxy (a) is much closer to us than the others and appears aligned with the others just by chance.

fields.name: NGC1788
fields.description: Distance: 2000 ly. This reflection nebula in Orion is the site of formation of a young star cluster. It appears blue in colour due to blue wavelengths of light scattering off gas and dust in the nebula. Use a colour exposure of 5s.

fields.name: NGC2169
fields.description: Distance: 3000 ly. This open cluster was discovered in 1784 by William Herschel. Use a colour exposure of 1s on this object

fields.name: NGC2186
fields.description: Distance: 5000 ly. This open cluster was discovered in 1786 by William Herschel. Use a colour exposure of 5s on this object

fields.name: NGC7177
fields.description: Distance: 49.9 million ly. This small spiral galaxy contains a central bulge surrounded by a bright disc. Use a 3 colour exposure of 45s on this object.

fields.name: NGC7339
fields.description: Distance: 57.1 million ly. This is an edge-on spiral galaxy, best images with a 45-60s colour exposure.

fields.name: NGC2452
fields.description: Distance: 11,000 ly. Discovered by Herschel in 1837. A 45s colour exposure images this object well.

fields.name: NGC2525
fields.description: Distance: 68.7 million ly. This is an impressive face-on barred spiral galaxy, best imaged in colour with a 45s exposure time.

fields.name: NGC2298
fields.description: Distance: 34900 ly. This small globular cluster was discovered in 1826 by James Dunlop. A 5-10s colour exposure produces a lovely image of this globular cluster.

fields.name: NGC2627
fields.description: Distance: 6,500 ly. NGC 2627, containing about 60 faint stars, spans a diameter of 11 arcmin in the constellation of Pyxis so is best viewed in mosaic mode. Use a 5s colour exposure on this object for best results.

fields.name: NGC2658
fields.description: Distance: 1532 ly. This open cluster contains about 80 stars. A 5s colour exposure is recommended for this cluster.

fields.name: NGC2613
fields.description: Distance: 65 million ly. This is a fine example of a spiral galaxy inclined from our line of sight so that we see it nearly edge-on. A 30-60s colour exposure is recommended for this object.

fields.name: NGC2888
fields.description: Distance: 106 million ly. This is a small elliptical galaxy, best viewed with a 45s colour exposure.

fields.name: M54
fields.description: Distance: 87400 ly. This higly concentrated globular cluster has a core which measures approx. 2.1 arcmin in diameter, but has outer stars which spread out to as much as 9 arcmin from the centre.

fields.name: M18
fields.description: Distance: 4,900ly. This poor open cluster has only about 20 members.

fields.name: M8
fields.description: Distance: 5100 ly. This large diffuse emission nebula is also known as the Lagoon nebula. A single FT image will show the central region of this nebula, although a mosaic of the region will give a better overall view of this beautiful object.

fields.name: NGC121
fields.description: Distance: 210 thousand ly. This small globular cluster is part of the Small Magellanic Cloud, a small irregular galaxy orbiting our Milky Way galaxy. A 3 colour exposure of 10s is recommended for this object.

fields.name: NGC0371
fields.description: Distance: 210,000 ly. This bright cluster is situated in the Small Magellanic cloud, a small irregular galaxy orbiting our Milky Way galaxy.

fields.name: NGC2792
fields.description: Distance: 9,000 ly. This is a fairly small PN in the constellation of Vela. A 3 colour exposure time of 30s is recommended for this object.

fields.name: NGC2660
fields.description: Distance: 9212 ly. This open cluster looks very similar to a globular cluster. Try a 3 colour exposure of 5s on this region.

fields.name: IC2488
fields.description: Distance: 3700 ly. The stars in this open cluster are quite spaced out, and are mainly blue, although there are also a few yellow stars. Use a 3 colour exposure of 1s on this object.

fields.name: HCG2
fields.description: A triplet of galaxies with a fainter member (bottom left).

fields.name: HCG11
fields.description: This group comprises of a spiral galaxy surrounded by three small satellites galaxies.

fields.name: HCG14
fields.description: This group consists of an interacting triplet of galaxies.

fields.name: HCG15
fields.description: This is a group of six galaxies, the brightest galaxy (in the centre) is interacting with a galaxy towards the top of group.

fields.name: HCG16
fields.description: This image consists of two of the four interacting galaxies.  The closest pair show prominent tidal distortions. Both galaxies are symetric and a tail like feature extends eastwards from galaxy.

fields.name: HCG21
fields.description: This group consists of a loose galaxy triplet and a fainter pair of galaxies. The brightest galaxy has two extending spiral arms.

fields.name: HCG22
fields.description: This group consists of a triplet containing a large eliptical galaxy (NGC1199) and two spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG23
fields.description: This group of galaxies contains an accordant quartet and a small high-redshift galaxy.

fields.name: HCG25
fields.description: This group consists of an accordant quintet plus three other galaxies.

fields.name: HCG30
fields.description: This is a relatively loose quartet of mostly spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG88
fields.description: This is a loose quartet of spiral galaxies, the brightest is also a radio and infrared source.

fields.name: HCG89
fields.description: This is a faint, loose quartet of sipiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG90
fields.description: This is a quartet of interacting galaxies.  Galaxy (top middle) has a prominent dust lane.

fields.name: HCG91
